<h2 id="simplest" class="coloured">Simplest search</h2>
<p>The simplest search possible is for a Surname in a County: leaving the Record type box blank wil return baptisms, marriages and burials. This could be useful for an uncommon surname, but most names will return too many records to display more than the first 250 found. Note that the results are found in no particular order.</p>

<p>[ Brandis in WAR? or Shorten in NFK? or both? ]</p>

<p>The following examples illustrate the effects of using the other search options so that all the matching records can be found.</p>

<hr class="rule" />

<h2 id="simple" class="coloured">Simple search for a baptism</h2>

<p class="flush--bottom">You can search the database for baptisms in a County by:</p>
<ul>
    <li>entering a <strong>Surname</strong> </li>
    <li>selecting a <strong>County</strong> from the drop down list </li>  
    <li>selecting <strong>Baptism</strong> from the Record type box</li>
</ul>

<figure class="site">
    <%= image_tag 'images/search 01.PNG', alt: 'Search 01', title: 'Search 01', data: { rel: '225x255' }, height: 540, width: 842 %>
    <figcaption>search 01.png: A search on surname, county and record type </figcaption>
</figure>

<p>This search gives the following results:</p>

<figure class="site">
    <%= image_tag 'images/search000.PNG', alt: 'Search000', title: 'Search000', data: { rel: '225x255' }, height: 520, width: 842 %>
    <figcaption>search000.png</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>The first thing to notice is the number of results displayed is 250, the maximum that will be found for a single search. Note also that the Surname column contains the Surname of the Father which may or may not be known. In this specific example the first set of records were retrieved based on the Mother's surname. [ ?? ]</p>

